  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Supporting IDPs to access secure land and housing</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In 2019, the Government of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan (GoIRA) promulgated Presidential Decree 305 (PD 305). The PD 305 provides documented  protracted IDPs and returnees the legal right to apply for land allocations and housing support from the state.  In doing so, it provides a durable solution to tenure insecurity and poor living conditions suffered by millions of returnees currently in Afghanistan, and those expected to return: in 2019 alone, an estimated 620,000 Afghans returned from Iran and Pakistan.   Land allocations are made in new settlements (or &#x2018;townships&#x2019;), located on vacant land in peripheral urban areas that meet the PD 305 criteria for sustainable settlements. Beneficiaries, selected following a vulnerability assessment, receive land titles and housing support to foment socioeconomic development. The SHURA project, implemented by GoIRA with technical support from UN-Habitat, is operationalizing the PD 305 in two pilot sites in Kabul and Herat, with a view to up-scaling nationally in the medium term. To date, however, protracted IDPs have faced challenges accessing the scheme. According to UN-Habitat analysis, out of the 13,000 families that registered for land since in Kabul and Herat since January 2020, around 1-2 per cent are  protracted IDPs, while 98-99 percent are returnees. 

In response, this project aims to provide durable solutions for protracted IDPs in Afghanistan to promote sustainable socioeconomic development, reintegration and build peace by providing around 10,000 protracted IDP households with HLP support to enable their access to land allocation mechanisms under the Presidential Decree 305 in Kabul and Herat. The project will also develop Standard Operating Procedures that feed into GoIRA and humanitarian partners&apos;  Action Plans to facilitate HLP support for protracted IDPs nationally.</narrative>
  </description>
